The paper discusses the development of interactive document browsers for scientific research reports, which involves capturing the structure of the reports and using it to support browsing. This involves aspects of information retrieval (cs.IR) and digital libraries (cs.DL), as well as human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and natural language processing (cs.CL). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of conceptual modeling frameworks (cs.CY) to facilitate interlinked digital libraries.
